% \item completes {R}'s string handling functions with
% useful functions from other programming languages.
% % and duplicates existing API :/
% \end{itemize}
% \end{quote}

In order to significantly broaden the array of string processing
operations and assure that they are portable, in 2013 the current
author developed the open source \textit{stringi} package
(pronounced ``stringy'', IPA \textipa{[{stringi}]}).
Its API was compatible with that of early \textit{stringr}'s,
which some users found convenient. However, for the processing of text
in different locales, which are plentiful, \textit{stringi} relies
on \textit{ICU} -- \textit{International Components for Unicode}
(see \url{https://icu.unicode.org/}) -- a mature library that
fully conforms with the Unicode standard and which provides globalisation
support for a broad range of other software applications as well, from
web browsers to database systems. Services not covered by \textit{ICU}
were implemented from scratch to guarantee that they are as efficient
as possible.

Over the years, \textit{stringi} confirmed itself as robust,
production-quality software; for many years now it has been one of the
most often downloaded {R} extensions. Interestingly, in 2015 the
aforementioned \textit{stringr} package has been rewritten as a
set of wrappers around some of the \textit{stringi} functions instead of
the base {R} ones.
% \textit{stringr} currently exports \Sexpr{length(ls("package:stringr"))} objects
In Section~14.7 of \textit{{R} for Data Science}
\citep{GrolemundWickham2017:rdatascience}
we read: \textit{\textit{stringr} is useful when you're learning because
it exposes a minimal set of functions, which have been carefully picked
to handle the most common string manipulation functions. \textit{stringi},
on the other hand, is designed to be comprehensive. It contains almost
every function you might ever need: \textit{stringi} has 250 functions to
\textit{stringr}'s 49}.
Also, it is worth noting that the recently-introduced \textit{stringx}
package \citep{stringx} supplies a \textit{stringi}-based set of portable
and efficient replacements for and enhancements of the base {R}
functions.

