\subsection{Joining}

Below we describe the functions that are related to string concatenation.


\paragraph{Operator \texttt{\%s+\%}.}
To join  the corresponding strings in two character vectors,
we may use the binary \texttt{\%s+\%} operator:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
x <- c("tasty", "delicious", "yummy", NA)
x %s+% " " %s+% c("spam", "bacon")
@\end{verbatim}

% character(0) %s+% c("spam", "bacon")

% This operator is vectorised in exactly the same manner
% as other arithmetic operators in {R}.
% In particular, the recycling rule is used if the inputs are of different
% lengths. If one of the arguments is empty, the result is a zero-length
% vector as well. Moreover, \textit{stringi} \textit{does} enforce the consistent
% propagation of missing values
% (unlike the built-in \texttt{paste()} function):
%
% <<>>=
% x <- c("spam", "bacon", "", "sausage", NA, "spam")
% x %s+% "!"
% @




\paragraph{Flattening.}
The elements in a character vector can be joined (``aggregated'')
to form a single string via a call to  \texttt{stri\_flatten()}:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_flatten(stri_omit_na(x), collapse=", ")
@\end{verbatim}

\noindent
Note that the token separator, given by the \texttt{collapse} argument,
defaults to the empty string.



\paragraph{Generalisation.}
Both the \texttt{\%s+\%} operator and the \texttt{stri\_flatten()} function
are generalised by
\texttt{stri\_join()} (alias: \texttt{stri\_paste()}, \texttt{stri\_c()}):

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_join(c("X", "Y", "Z"), 1:6, "a")  # sep="", collapse=NULL
@\end{verbatim}

By default, the \texttt{sep} argument, which controls how corresponding
strings are delimited, is set to the empty string
(like in the base \texttt{paste0()} but unlike in \texttt{paste()}).
Moreover, \texttt{collapse} is \texttt{NULL}, which means that
the resulting outputs will not be joined to form a single string.
This can be changed if need be:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_join(c("X", "Y", "Z"), 1:6, "a", sep="_", collapse=", ")
@\end{verbatim}



\noindent
Note how the two (1st, 3rd) shorter vectors were {recycled} to match
the longest (2nd) vector's length. The latter was of numeric type,
but it was implicitly coerced via a call to \texttt{as.character()}.


% paste()  sep="" by default
% paste0() sep=" "
% NA handling, character(0), UTF-8 output as usual in stringi


% \ifnotJSSversion
More examples:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_join(pythons[, 2], pythons[, 1], sep=", ")
outer(LETTERS[1:3], 1:5, stri_join, sep=".")  # outer product
@\end{verbatim}
% \fi



\paragraph{Duplicating.}
To duplicate given strings, we call
\texttt{stri\_dup()} or the \texttt{\%s*\%} operator:


\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_dup(letters[1:5], 1:5)
@\end{verbatim}

The above is synonymous with \texttt{letters[1:5] \%s*\% 1:5}.


\paragraph{Within-list joining.}
There is also a convenience function that applies \texttt{stri\_flatten()}
on each character vector in a given list:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
words <- list(c("spam", "bacon", "sausage", "spam"), c("eggs", "spam"))
stri_join_list(words, sep=", ")  # collapse=NULL
@\end{verbatim}

% \ifnotJSSversion
\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_join_list(words, sep=", ", collapse=";\n")
@\end{verbatim}
% \fi

\noindent
This way, a list of character vectors can be converted to
a character vector. Such sequences of variable length sequences of
strings are generated by, amongst others,
\texttt{stri\_sub\_all()} and \texttt{stri\_extract\_all()}.






\subsection{Extracting and replacing substrings}

Next group of functions deals with the extraction and replacement
of particular sequences of code points in given strings.

\paragraph{Indexing vectors.}
Recall that in order to select a subsequence from any {R} vector,
we use the square-bracket operator\footnote{More precisely, \texttt{x[i]}
is a syntactic sugar for a call to \texttt{`[`(x, i)}.
Moreover, if \texttt{x} is a list, \texttt{x[[i]]} can be used to
extract its \texttt{i}-th element (alias \texttt{`[[`(x, i)}).
Knowing the ``functional'' form of the operators allows us to, for instance,
extract all first elements from each vector in a list
by simply calling \texttt{sapply(x, "[[", 1)}.}
with an index vector consisting of either
non-negative integers, negative integers,
or logical values\footnote{If an object's \texttt{names} attribute is set,
indexing with a character vector is also possible.}.

For example, here is how to select specific elements in a vector:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
x <- c("spam", "buckwheat", "", NA, "bacon")
x[1:3]                           # from 1st to 3rd string
x[c(1, length(x))]               # 1st and last
@\end{verbatim}

\noindent
Exclusion of elements at specific positions can be performed like:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
x[-1]                            # all but 1st
@\end{verbatim}

\noindent
Filtering based on a logical vector can be used to extract
strings fulfilling desired criteria:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
x[!stri_isempty(x) & !is.na(x)]
@\end{verbatim}


\paragraph{Extracting substrings.}
A character vector is, in its very own essence, a sequence of
sequences of code points.
To extract specific substrings from each string in a collection,
we can use the \texttt{stri\_sub()} function.

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
y <- "spam, egg, spam, spam, bacon, and spam"
stri_sub(y, 18)             # from 18th code point to end
stri_sub(y, 12, to=15)      # from 12th to 15th code point (inclusive)
@\end{verbatim}

Negative indices count from the end of a string.

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_sub(y, -15, length=5)  # 5 code points from 15th last
@\end{verbatim}




\paragraph{\texttt{stri\_sub\_all()} function.}
% \ifnotJSSversion
% The \texttt{stri\_sub()}  function is of course vectorised with respect
% to all its arguments
% (the subsetted character vector, \texttt{from}, and \texttt{to} or \texttt{length}).
% If one of the vectors is of smaller length than the other ones,
% the recycling rule is applied as usual. For instance:
%
% <<>>=
% stri_sub(y, c(1, 12, 18), length=4) # different substrings of one string
% stri_sub(x[c(1, 2, 4)], from=-3)    # same substrings of different strings
% stri_sub(x[c(1, 2, 4)],
%   c(-4, -2, -5))  # different substrings of different strings
% @
% \fi
If some deeper vectorisation level is necessary, \texttt{stri\_sub\_all()}
comes in handy. It extracts multiple (possibly different) substrings
from all the strings provided:


\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
(z <- stri_sub_all(
              c("spam",     "bacon", "sorghum"),
  from   = list(c(1, 3, 4), -3,      c(2, 4)),
  length = list(1,           3,      c(4, 3))))
@\end{verbatim}

As the number of substrings to extract from each string might vary,
the result is a list of character strings.
We have obtained:
substrings of length 1 starting at positions 1, 3, and 4 in \texttt{x[1]},
then a length-3 substring that starts at the 3rd code point
from the end of \texttt{x[2]},
and length-4 and -3 substrings starting at, respectively,
the 2nd and 4th code point
of \texttt{x[3]} (where \texttt{x} denotes the subsetted vector).


% \ifnotJSSversion
Recall that the strings may all be concatenated by means of the
aforementioned \texttt{stri\_join\_list()} function.

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_join_list(z, sep=", ")
@\end{verbatim}



There is also a more flexible version
of the built-in \texttt{simplify2array()} function whose
aim is to convert such lists to matrices.

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_list2matrix(z, by_row=TRUE, fill="", n_min=5)
@\end{verbatim}
% \fi


% Here is a way to extract
% non-consecutive substrings from each string --
% ones that consist of the first and the last letter:
%
% <<>>=
% stri_join_list(stri_sub_all(x[c(1, 2, 4)], c(1, -1), length=1))
% @






\paragraph{``From--to'' and ``from--length'' matrices.}
The second parameter of both \texttt{stri\_sub()} and \texttt{stri\_sub\_list()}
can also be fed with a two-column matrix
of the form \texttt{cbind(from, to)}. Here, the first column
gives the start indices and the second column defines the end ones.
Such matrices are generated, amongst others, by the \texttt{stri\_locate\_*()}
functions (see below for details).

% \ifnotJSSversion
\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
(from_to <- cbind(from=c(1, 12, 18), to=c(4, 15, 21))) # +optional labels
stri_sub(y, from_to)
@\end{verbatim}


\noindent Another example (the recycling rule):
% \fi

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
(from_to <- matrix(1:8, ncol=2, byrow=TRUE))
stri_sub(c("abcdefgh", "ijklmnop"), from_to)
@\end{verbatim}

\noindent
Due to recycling, this has extracted
elements at positions 1:2 from the 1st string,
at 3:4 from the 2nd one, 5:6 from the 1st, and 7:8 from the 2nd again.

Note the difference between the above output and the following one:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_sub_all(c("abcdefgh", "ijklmnop"), from_to)
@\end{verbatim}

This time, we extract four identical sections from each of the two inputs.


\medskip
Moreover, if the second column of the index matrix is named
\texttt{"length"} (and only if this is exactly the case),
i.e., the indexer is of the form \texttt{cbind(from, length=length)},
extraction will be based on the extracted chunk size.




% \ifnotJSSversion
\paragraph{Permuting code points.}
Somewhat related to the above are different ways to construct
various permutations (possibly with replacement) of code points in a string:

\begin{verbatim}<<echo=-1>>=
set.seed(123)
stri_join_list(stri_sub_all("spam", c(4, 3, 2, 3, 1), length=1))
stri_rand_shuffle("bacon")  # random order
stri_reverse("spam")        # reverse order
@\end{verbatim}
% \fi

\paragraph{Replacing substrings.}
\texttt{stri\_sub\_replace()} returns a version
of a character vector with some chunks replaced by other
strings:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_sub_replace(c("abcde", "ABCDE"),
  from=c(2, 4), length=c(1, 2), replacement=c("X", "uvw"))
@\end{verbatim}

\noindent
The above replaced ``\texttt{b}'' (the length-1 substring
starting at index 2 of the 1st string) with ``\texttt{X}''
and ``\texttt{DE}''
(the length-2 substring at index 4 of the 2nd string)
with ``\texttt{uvw}''.


Similarly, \texttt{stri\_sub\_replace\_all()} replaces
multiple substrings within each string in a character vector:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
stri_sub_replace_all(
                   c("abcde",  "ABCDE"),
  from        = list(c(2, 4),  c(0,    3,   6)),
  length      = list(  1,      c(0,    2,   0)),
  replacement = list(  "Z",    c("uu", "v", "wwww")))
@\end{verbatim}

\noindent
Note how we have obtained the insertion of new content
at the start and the end of the 2nd input.


\paragraph{Replacing substrings in-place.}
The corresponding {replacement functions} modify
a character vector in-place:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
y <- "spam, egg, spam, spam, bacon, and spam"
stri_sub(y, 7, length=3) <- "spam"  # in-place replacement, egg → spam
print(y)                            # y has changed
@\end{verbatim}

Note that the state of \texttt{y} has changed in such a way that the
substring of length 3 starting at the 7th code point
was replaced by a length-4 content.

Many replacements within a single string are also possible:

\begin{verbatim}<<>>=
y <- "aa bb cc"
stri_sub_all(y, c(1, 4, 7), length=2) <- c("A", "BB", "CCC")
print(y)                            # y has changed
@\end{verbatim}

\noindent
This has replaced 3 length-2 chunks within \texttt{y} with new content.


% \clearpage


