We have reviewed the key design principles and facilities available in
\textit{stringi}, including numerous operations
that  help implement and optimise data processing pipelines.
Let us again stress that many package features are provided by \textit{ICU}, which
is a platform-independent project. Hence, information
presented above might be of interest to statisticians and data scientists
employing different programming environments as well.



Users seeking Unicode-aware replacements for base {R}
string processing functions are kindly referred to the \textit{stringx}
package \citep{stringx}, which is a set of wrappers around \textit{stringi}
offering a more classic API
(functions such as \texttt{grepl()}, \texttt{substring()}, etc.,
compare Table~\ref{Tab:oldstringr}).


\textit{stringi} functions can also be accessed from within {C++}
code. Authors of statistical/data analysis software who would like to
speed up their projects are encouraged to check out
the \textit{ExampleRcppStringi} package available at
\url{https://github.com/gagolews/ExampleRcppStringi},
which serves as a working prototype developed using \textit{Rcpp} \citep{rcppbook}.








